Tip of the week: the door from the Advanced 3D Printing Kit is one of the most effective methods to create a stable printing environment inside your Ultimaker 2+. It will keep the warmth from the heated build plate inside the printer, enabling you to print with more advanced materials.

Meet our guest on the podcast for this week: @andrewmorgan__ Living in Long Beach, CA he now operates a low volume, high quality clothing manufacturing operation where he has built long-term relationships with his customers and works on his own collection. Born and raised in Florence, MA one of his first passions was riding scooters. At just 16 he launched his first business 'System Scooters' in which he was making aftermarket parts at his vocational high school where he was learning metal manufacturing and was able to sell the products and make 100% profit. Years down the line he launched his first clothing company 'Exito Clothing' which was influenced by street wear brands like @diamondsupplyco and @bennygold. With sponsoring local skaters he was able to gain traction and eventually was selling products in nearby skate shops. Wanting to change it up and get into high quality design and products, he spent 2 years in his basement mastering his craft and then made the move to the West Coast where he now resides with his fiancée.  We discuss how scootering brought him confidence in himself, being patient and not rushing the final product, how he started off in Cali with just a trunk full of stuff to now a full manufacturing operation with high-end machinery, his tattooing hustle helping him make money and not forcing him to get a job, why he would sit down with Will Smith if he could and not wasting your time doing something you don't love. ⚡️🌐| link in bio 🗣🎙

It's Chinese aviation with western characteristics.
The Comac C919 has just completed its first test flight. But the aircraft might not have got off the ground without help from the west.
The first time China attempted to build a large passenger jet, it tried to reverse-engineer a Boeing 707 that crash-landed in Xinjiang in 1971. This time Beijing took a different path: it bought parts from European and US aviation companies rather than stealing their technology. 
Is Xi Jinping's plan to turn the country into an aviation powerhouse one step closer to fruition?
